{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17509916","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17509916"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:21:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:21:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11464"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11464","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11464"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.5,0.14,0.17,0.17,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4096"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"84804"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4096","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4096"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11464"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69100"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"3461"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9269"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4836"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4962"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5248"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42605"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44529"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"84804","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/84804"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with three hours of epigastric pain. For the past few months he has experienced similar pain triggered by meals, settling within an hour with paracetamol. Today the pain is sharp, rated 9/10, and localised to the epigastrium. Paracetamol has not provided relief. He feels nauseated, sweaty and slightly feverish. He has a medical history of sleeve gastrectomy one year ago with subsequent weight loss from BMI 55 to 35 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E, appendectomy, and type II diabetes mellitus treated with metformin. He does not take any other regular medications. He does not smoke or drink alcohol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears distressed and diaphoretic. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 150/95 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, and temperature 38.2\u00b0C. There is localised tenderness and guarding in the epigastrium and right upper quadrant. An electrocardiogram shows sinus tachycardia.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acute cholecystitis","Acute cholangitis","Acute pancreatitis","Peptic ulcer disease","Gastro-oesophageal reflux disease"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features highly suggestive of \u003Cstrong\u003Eacute cholecystitis\u003C/strong\u003E: right upper quadrant pain and tenderness, fever, and a history of postprandial pain. His recent sleeve gastrectomy and rapid weight loss are significant risk factors for gallstone formation due to altered bile composition and metabolism. The absence of jaundice makes uncomplicated cholecystitis more likely than other biliary pathologies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute cholangitis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with Charcot\u0027s triad of right upper quadrant pain, fever, and jaundice. The absence of jaundice and the strong risk factors for gallstone disease make cholangitis less likely than cholecystitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute pancreatitis\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes severe epigastric pain radiating to the back. While gallstones can cause pancreatitis, the localised right upper quadrant tenderness and history of postprandial symptoms are more consistent with cholecystitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeptic ulcer disease\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes epigastric pain that improves with food intake. The presence of fever, right upper quadrant tenderness, and strong risk factors for gallstone disease make this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGastro-oesophageal reflux disease\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes retrosternal burning pain that worsens when supine or after meals. The presence of fever, right upper quadrant signs, and the acute severe nature of the pain make this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Sudden weight loss and prior bariatric surgery increase the risk of gallstone formation due to altered bile composition and metabolism.","Murphy\u0027s sign (RUQ tenderness on deep inspiration) and fever are key clinical features of acute cholecystitis.","The triad of RUQ pain, fever, and jaundice suggests cholangitis rather than uncomplicated cholecystitis."],"references":["Jones MW, Genova R, O\u0027Rourke MC. Acute Cholecystitis. In: StatPearls [online].  [Updated 2021 Sep 9]. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK459171/","Miura F, Takada T, Strasberg SM, et al. TG13 flowchart for the management of acute cholangitis and cholecystitis. J Hepatobiliary Pancreat Sci. 2013 Jan;20(1):47-54. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/23307003/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69100"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11464"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69100","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/69100"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-11T13:11:16+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-11T13:11:16+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4096"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"84804"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"